     <h1>FAQ's for Parents</h1> 
     <h2><strong>Inquiring minds ask Stu Cleek, Associate Dean for Residence Life</strong></h2> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">Year after year, parents seem to wonder the same sort of things. We hope to anticipate some of those questions before you even get the chance to ask them!</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;"><strong>Q:&nbsp; What changes can I expect in my student while at Westmont?</strong></p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">A:&nbsp; In their Westmont years, your student will be asking fundamental questions about who they are.&nbsp; These questions can be scary to parents because they may explore different answers than you would.&nbsp; That is a possibility, but the process — the asking and answering and living with the results — is the beginning of a life journey. Try to be patient as he or she works through the process. On graduation day, your student will no doubt be different than the person you sent to Westmont, but you will be proud of&nbsp;<br> the man or woman he or she becomes at Westmont.</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;"><strong>Q: How often should I visit, and how often should I encourage my son or daughter to come home?</strong></p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">A:&nbsp; Visit infrequently and always call before coming. Students look forward to parents visiting, but the weekends are also times to build relationships and (hopefully) work on class assignments. None of this will happen if students are at home or parents are at college. I suggest that students do not go home until the fall four-day break and that parents visit just once a semester (first-year parents weekend could be a great time to do so). This allows students to maintain family relationships but gives them the space to create a new “community.”</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;"><strong>Q:&nbsp; Are there any topics I should avoid writing or talking about with my student?</strong></p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">A:&nbsp; Good question, and yes there are. Don’t ask too often about grades and academic performance (although I know it goes against every instinct in your body).&nbsp; Students are often under a great deal of pressure and your questions will not help. Instead, try asking what he or she is learning. Avoid asking those, “I’m-secretly-checking-up-on-you questions.” Try to avoid mentioning how expensive college is as students are usually well aware of the investment you are making. Avoid asking if they are dating, which may add to pressure to “find a mate” at Westmont. Let your student lead the conversation and trust that they will talk to you when they are ready.&nbsp;</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;"><strong>Q:&nbsp; What do I do when my student calls and asks to come home for good?</strong></p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">A:&nbsp; First, don’t panic.&nbsp; Many parents receive a call like this in the first year. Just listen! Most of the time students don’t want you to fix the problem but just want you to sympathetically listen. After listening, suggest that your student seek out resources available to them at Westmont. You can always suggest they see someone in the student life office or their resident director.&nbsp; Try not to dwell on the call. Many times the student will feel much better after calling home and mom and dad will feel worse!</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;"><strong>Q:&nbsp; I don’t want my student to make poor lifestyle choices. How can we keep him or her away from these influences?</strong></p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">A:&nbsp; The reality is that you can’t. The opportunity to experiment is a part of college sub-culture. Westmont does have policies that make poor lifestyles choices more difficult, but we cannot control your student. You must trust that the foundation you have formed will help your student make sound judgments and learn from his or her mistakes.&nbsp; Your student needs to know that you love him or her, regardless of the mistakes that he or she makes.</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;"><strong>Q:&nbsp; Will I be notified if there is a discipline problem with my student, and are there helpful ways for me to respond if my student does “get in trouble?”</strong></p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">A:&nbsp; Westmont views its students as apprentice adults who are in the midst of a maturation process. They are developing into people who make life choices that are wise, healthy, and reflective of a desire to be followers of Christ. The college also recognizes the important role and investment that parents have in their student’s life.&nbsp; We believe that honest communication between students and parents fosters trust.&nbsp; For these reasons, while we tend not to notify parents, we strongly encourage students to call home when they have breached a behavioral expectation. Not only is it a Westmont policy, it’s the law.&nbsp; The Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA) of 1974 (also known as the Buckley Amendment) limits disclosure of confidential materials only to those released by written consent of the student. In spite of our encouragement, we know some students will choose not to seek counsel and support from their parents during such circumstances. Therefore, in some instances involving drug use, and alcoholic infractions, we do require parental notification.</p> 
     <p style="text-align:justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We believe parents can play an important role in maximizing their student’s learning experience in a disciplinary situation.&nbsp; In this regard, probably the most helpful thing you can do is to resist the strong urge you may have to be too involved. Rather than trying to negotiate the process for them, try to see your role as listening, understanding, and offering feedback to your student as he or she negotiates his or her own way through the process as a key component in their learning.</p> 
